    (7,'Computer Science and Economics','economic privacy','BEYOND THE PRIVACY PARADOX: OBJECTIVE VERSUS RELATIVE RISK IN PRIVACY DECISION MAKING.','Adjerid, Idris; Peer, Eyal; Acquisti, Alessandro','MIS Quarterly','Adjerid, Idris, et al. “Beyond the Privacy Paradox: Objective Versus Relative Risk in Privacy Decision Making.” MIS Quarterly, vol. 42, no. 2, June 2018, pp. 465-A5. EBSCOhost, doi:10.25300/MISQ/2018/14316.',NULL,'http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/eds/viewarticle/render?data=dGJyMPPp44rp2%2fdV0%2bnjisfk5Ie46a9KsKyxT66k63nn5Kx94um%2bUa2osEewpq9Rnqq4S7Kwrk%2bet8s%2b8ujfhvHX4Yzn5eyB4rOvTbOrt0mzqbBRpOLfhuWz44ak2uBV4OrmPvLX5VW%2fxKR57LOvSreqsUuvqLI%2b5OXwhd%2fqu4ji3MSN6uLSffbq&vid=2&sid=72f7bc07-65ef-42f5-99e2-66be6d4b7e3d@sessionmgr4007','The article presents a study on both the objective and relative risks involved with privacy decision making. Topics include the impact of changes in the objective risk of disclosure and the impact of changes in the relative perceptions of risk of disclosure on hypothetical and actual consumer privacy choices, a decrease in objective risk going from hypothetical to actual choice settings, and an increase in relative risk going from hypothetical to actual choice settings.'),
    (13,'Computer Science and Economics','technology privacy change','Technology Transience and Learner Data: Shifting Notions of Privacy in Online Learning','Dennen, Vanessa P','Quarterly Review of Distance Education','Dennen, Vanessa P. “Technology Transience and Learner Data: Shifting Notions of Privacy in Online Learning.” Quarterly Review of Distance Education, vol. 16, no. 2, Jan. 2015, pp. 45–59. EBSCOhost, search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=eric&AN=EJ1143781&site=eds-live.',NULL,'http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/eds/viewarticle/render?data=dGJyMPPp44rp2%2fdV0%2bnjisfk5Ie46a9KsKyxT66k63nn5Kx94um%2bUa2osEewpq9Rnqe4S7ewrkyexss%2b8ujfhvHX4Yzn5eyB4rOvT7artU2vrbBLpOLfhuWz44ak2uBV4%2bjne6Tq33%2b7t8w%2b3%2bS7Xcinr0yxrbZJpNztiuvX8lXu2uRe8%2bLqbOPu8gAA&vid=3&sid=f23ec8a9-4291-4bdd-9b2e-133c036dd947@sessionmgr4006','The technologies that support online learning are continuously evolving, providing instructors and students with a continuous stream of new tools, features, and functionalities for existing tools. During an online course, instructors and students generate and share a tremendous amount of data using these tools. These data are often created in contexts where privacy concerns and safeguards are similarly evolving and uncertain. This article discusses online privacy concerns and emergent solutions in online learning contexts where technology transience is present. It focuses on issues such as legal rights, issues raised by emerging educational technologies, and manners by which institutions, instructors'),
    (16,'Computer Science and Economics','technology privacy change','On Educating Patrons on Privacy and Maximizing Library Resources.',NULL,'Information Technology & Libraries','“On Educating Patrons on Privacy and Maximizing Library Resources.” Information Technology & Libraries, vol. 38, no. 3, Sept. 2019, pp. 4–7. EBSCOhost, doi:10.6017/ital.v38i3.11571.',NULL,'http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/eds/Citations/FullTextLinkClick?sid=33074af4-9734-42b4-b04c-0f7b99cce731@sessionmgr4007&vid=0&id=pdfFullText','Libraries are one of our most valuable institutions. They cater to people of all demographics and provide services to patrons they wouldn''t be able to get anywhere else. The list of services libraries provide is extensive and comprehensive, although unfortunately, there are significant gaps in what our services can offer, particularly those regarding technology advancement and patron privacy. Though library classes on educating patrons'' privacy protection are a valiant effort, we can do so much more and lead the way, maybe not for the privacy industry but for our communities and patrons. Creating a strong foundational knowledge will help patrons leverage these new skills in their day to day lives as well as help them educate their families about common privacy issues. In this column, we''ll explore some of the ways libraries can utilize their current resources as well as provide ideas on how we can maximize their effectiveness and roll new technologies into their operations.'),
    (19,'Computer Science and Economics','technology privacy change','The Future of Blockchain: As Technology Spreads, It May Warrant More Privacy Protection for Information Stored with Blockchain','Longman, Ashley N.','North Carolina Banking Institute','Longman, Ashley N. “The Future of Blockchain: As Technology Spreads, It May Warrant More Privacy Protection for Information Stored with Blockchain.” North Carolina Banking Institute, 2019, p. 111. EBSCOhost, search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=edshol&AN=edshol.hein.journals.ncbj23.8&site=eds-live.',NULL,'http://eds.a.ebscohost.com/eds/SmartLink/OpenIlsLink?sid=8f1119f3-2493-4a6c-b514-322a4604c1e1@sessionmgr4008&vid=0&sl=smartlink&st=ilslink_new&sv=sdbn%253Dedshol%2526pbt%253DAcademic%2520Journal%2526issn%253D10967249%2526ttl%253DNorth%252520Carolina%252520Banking%252520Institute%2526stp%253DC%2526asi%253DY%2526ldc%253D%2526lna%253DSFX%252520Link%252520Resolver%252520%252528all%252520content%252529%252520%252528EDS%252520Link%252529%2526lca%253DfullText%2526lo%255Fan%253Dedshol%25252Ehein%25252Ejournals%25252Encbj23%25252E8&su=https%3A%2F%2Fucelinks%2Ecdlib%2Eorg%2Fsfx%5Flocal%3Fgenre%3Darticle%26atitle%3DThe%2520Future%2520of%2520Blockchain%253A%2520As%2520Technology%2520Spreads%252C%2520It%2520May%2520Warrant%2520More%2520Privacy%2520Protection%2520for%2520Information%2520Stored%2520with%2520Blockchain%26title%3DNorth%20Carolina%20Banking%20Institute%26issn%3D10967249%26isbn%3D%26volume%3D23%26issue%3D%26date%3D20190101%26aulast%3DLongman%2C%20Ashley%20N%2E%26spage%3D111%26pages%3D111%2D138%26sid%3DEBSCO%3AHeinOnline%3Aedshol%2Ehein%2Ejournals%2Encbj23%2E8','None'),
